HEADWORD: Slack
<hw>Slack</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Slag</er>.]</ety> <def>Small coal; also, coal dust; culm.</def>
<rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slack
<hw>Slack</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>slakki</ets> a slope on a
mountain edge.]</ety> <def>A valley, or small, shallow dell.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Grose.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Slack
<hw>Slack</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Slacker</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Slackest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>slak</ets>, AS.
<ets>sleac</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>slak</ets>, OHG. <ets>slah</ets>,
Prov. G. <ets>schlack</ets>, Icel. <ets>slakr</ets>, Sw.
<ets>slak</ets>; cf. Skr. <ets>s⟦rsdot⟧j</ets> to let loose, to throw.
Cf. <er>Slake</er>.]</ety> <def>Lax; not tense; not hard drawn; not
firmly extended; <as>as, a <ex>slack</ex> rope</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Weak; not holding fast; <as>as, a <ex>slack</ex>
hand</as>.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Remiss; backward; not using due diligence or care;
not earnest or eager; <as>as, <ex>slack</ex> in duty or
service</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord is not <qex>slack</qex> concerning his promise, as some
men count slackness.</q> <rj><qau>2 Pet. iii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not violent, rapid, or pressing; slow; moderate;
easy; <as>as, business is <ex>slack</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With
<xex>slack</xex> pace.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Caesar . . . about sunset, hoisting sail with a <qex>slack</qex>
southwest, at midnight was becalmed.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Slack in stays</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>slow in
going about, as a ship.</cd> -- <col><b>Slack water</b></col>, <cd>the
time when the tide runs slowly, or the water is at rest; or the interval
between the flux and reflux of the tide.</cd> -- <col><b>Slack-water
navigation</b></col>, <cd>navigation in a stream the depth of which has
been increased, and the current diminished, by a dam or
dams.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Loose; relaxed; weak; remiss; backward; abated;
diminished; inactive; slow; tardy; dull.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Slack
<hw>Slack</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Slackly; <as>as,
<ex>slack</ex> dried hops</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slack</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Slack
<hw>Slack</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The part of anything that hangs
loose, having no strain upon it; <as>as, the <ex>slack</ex> of a rope or
of a sail</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

